The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, May 13, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Blue Star Ltd, an AC and refrigerator manufacturer, has posted a 5 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 32.55 crore in the year ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 31.04 crore in the previous year. The companys board has recommended a dividend of Rs 9 per share, a release said. Blue Stars total income during the year rose 19 per cent to Rs 716.06 crore, while order inflows rose 30 per cent to Rs 800.70 crore, it said. 																								 Tata Infotech Ltd has posted a 95 per cent rise in profit after tax at Rs 59.48 crore for the year ended March 2004 over the same period a year ago and announced 100 per cent dividend for 2003-04. The companys revenue for the period was Rs 598 crore, a rise of 29 per cent on a year-on-year basis, a Tata Infotech release said.																								 Indian Overseas Bank (IOB) has posted a 67 per cent jump in operating profit at Rs 1,325.20 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 794.13 crore in the previous year. The banks net profit rose to Rs 512.76 crore from Rs 416.10 crore. The bank had already paid an interim dividend of 12 per cent, managing director S. C. Gupta said. Subject to approval by the Reserve Bank, a final dividend of 8 per cent more was being proposed for 2003-04, taking the total to 20 per cent.																								 Magma Leasing Limited, a Calcutta-based NBFC, has recorded a 130 per cent rise in its net profit at Rs 17.63 crore against Rs 7.65 crore in the previous year. The company posted a 36 per cent rise on its total revenue in 2003-04. Managing director Sanjay Chamria said the total income touched Rs 82.08 crore from Rs 60.35 crore in the previous year.																								 Sun Microsystems has partnered with Paradox Studios, a Reliance group company, to boost the Java gaming market in the country. The tie-up will help us to leverage Suns vast technical expertise in helping gaming developers across the world as well as opening up new markets for Paradox, said Anurag Khurana, CEO, Paradox.																								 Lafarge India Pvt Ltd, a leading cement company, has launched Lafarge Concerto, a premium variant, in West Bengal. Concerto is an all-purpose cement that can be used for varied applications like roofing, foundations, beams, columns, plastering and brickwork.																								 Metro Dairy had the highest share of the ice cream retail market in Calcutta in 2003-04, according to the Retail Store Audit conducted by AC Neilsen ORG MARG Ltd. In April-March 2004, Metro Dairys ice cream had a 44 per cent market share of the total volume of ice cream retailed in Greater Calcutta. 																								 Hindustan Lever Ltd has priced Dove, its premium cleansing bar, at Rs 25 for 75 g. The company has established Dove as the mildest soap in the country after conducting certain tests mandated by the Bureau of Indian Standards. ADVERTISEMENT
